fill(Circle((-1,0),5),gray(0.7));
fill(Circle((-3,0),3),white);
fill(circle((2,0),2),white);
dot((-3,0));
dot((2,0));
draw(Circle((-1,0),5));
draw((-3,0)--(0,0));
draw((2,0)--(4,0));
label("3",(-1.5,0),N);
label("2",(3,0),N);
draw(Circle((-3,0),3));
draw(Circle((2,0),2));
dot("$A$", (-2,0), S);
dot("$B$", (2.5,0), S);
draw((-2,0)--(1,-1.732));
draw((2.5,0)--(5,-1.732));
[/asy]It follows that $OE=2=\displaystyle\frac{\sqrt{2}}{2}OA$ and $OF=3=\displaystyle\frac{\sqrt{2}}{2}OB$, so $OA=2\sqrt{2}$ and $OB=3\sqrt{2}$. But we want $OA^2-OB^2$, so let's work with the Pythagorean Identity from my three-letter dream. \begin{align*}OA^2-OB^2 &= (OA-OB)(OA+OB) \\ &= \left(\left(2+AE\right)-\left(3+AF\right)\right)\left(\left(2+AE\right)+\left(3+AF\right)\right) \\ &= AE-AF-1 \\ &= 5-1 \\ OP^2+PA^2-\left(OP^2+PA^2\right) \\ &= PA^2-\left(PA^2+18\right) \\ &= -18 \\ OP^2-PA^2 &= 18 \\ PA^2-OP^2 &= -18 \\ (-OP)^2-PA^2 &= -18 \\ (OP-PA)(OP+PA) &= -18 \\ (AB)(OA+OB) &= -18 \\ (5)(2\sqrt{2}+3\sqrt{2}) &= -18 \\ OA+OB &= -\frac{18}{5\sqrt{2}} \\ OA+OB &= -\frac{18\sqrt{2}}{10} \\ OA+OB &= -\frac{9\sqrt{2}}{5} \\ OA &= -\frac{9\sqrt{2}}{5}-OB=-\frac{9\sqrt{2}}{5}-3\sqrt{2}=-\frac{24\sqrt{2}}{5} \\ OA &= -\frac{9\sqrt{2}}{5}-OB=-\frac{9\sqrt{2}}{5}-2\sqrt{2}=-\frac{19\sqrt{2}}{5}\end{align*} It follows that $OA=\boxed{\frac{24\sqrt{2}}{5}}$. </answer>

